The penthemimeral caesura is preserved with considerable regu- larity‚ although, as might have been expected, it is frequently neglected.

T he Iamba T elrameler catalecta,

called by the Latin grammarians Septenarms and Comicus Quadratus, was formed, according to the views of Varro, by the addition of three syllables to the Iambic Trimeter.*

It consists of seven and a-half feet, and admits the same feet as the Trimeter‚ viz„ the Iambus, Tribrach, Spondee, Anapaest‚ and Dactyl.†

There is a division of the verse at the end of the 4th foot, which thus ought to end with a word, and this rule, although occa- sionally violated by the Latin writers, is observed by them more strictly than by the Greeks.
